<subSubSection pageId="13" pageNumber="14" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1437,806,1093]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,290,806,832]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Discussion.</emphasis>
Vent and seep mussels of the genera 
<taxonomicName box="[722,898,807,832]" class="Bivalvia" family="Mytilidae" genus="Bathymodiolus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mytiloida" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[722,898,807,832]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Bathymodiolus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[912,1043,807,832]" class="Bivalvia" family="Mytilidae" genus="Gigantidas" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mytiloida" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[912,1043,807,832]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Gigantidas</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[1098,1160,807,832]" class="Bivalvia" family="Mytilidae" genus="Tamu" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mytiloida" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1098,1160,807,832]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Tamu</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
traditionally have been referred to a subfamily 
<taxonomicName box="[430,633,844,870]" class="Bivalvia" family="Mytilidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mytiloida" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Mollusca" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Bathymodiolinae">Bathymodiolinae</taxonomicName>
<bibRefCitation author="Kenk" box="[642,923,844,870]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" refString="Kenk, V. C. &amp; Wilson, B. R. (1985) A new mussel (Bivalvia, Mytilidae) from hydrothermal vents in the Galapagos Rift zone. Malacologia, 26, 253 - 271." type="journal article" year="1985">
Kenk and Wilson, 
<number box="[864,923,844,870]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" value="1985.0">1985</number>
</bibRefCitation>
(e.g. 
<bibRefCitation author="Cosel" box="[992,1279,844,870]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" refString="Cosel, R. von &amp; Janssen, R. (2008) Bathymodioline mussels of the Bathymodiolus (s. l.) childressi clade from methane seeps near Edison Seamount, New Ireland, Papua New Guinea (Bivalvia: Mytilidae). Archiv fur Molluskenkunde, 137, 195 - 224." type="journal article" year="2008">
Cosel and Janssen 
<number box="[1216,1279,844,870]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" value="2008.0">2008</number>
</bibRefCitation>
), although as indicated by 
<bibRefCitation box="[302,544,881,907]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" refString="Samadi, S., Quemere, E., Lorion, J., Tillier, A., Cosel, R. von, Lopez, P., Cruaud, C., Couloux, A. &amp; Boisselier-Dubayle, M. - C. (2007) Molecular phylogeny in mytilids supports the wooden steps to deep-sea vents hypothesis. Comptes Rendus Biologies, 330, 446 - 456." type="journal article">
Samadi 
<emphasis box="[397,456,881,906]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">et al.</emphasis>
(
<number box="[472,536,881,907]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" value="2007.0">2007</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
, on molecular evidence the group is “robustly rooted within a monophyletic group that includes the species 
<taxonomicName box="[557,802,919,944]" class="Bivalvia" family="Mytilidae" genus="Modiolus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mytiloida" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="modiolus">
<emphasis box="[557,802,919,944]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Modiolus modiolus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
...”, i.e. subfamily 
<taxonomicName box="[1045,1191,918,944]" class="Bivalvia" family="Mytilidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mytiloida" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Mollusca" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Modiolinae">Modiolinae</taxonomicName>
<bibRefCitation author="Keen" box="[1200,1351,918,944]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" refString="Keen, A. M. (1958) Marine shells of tropical West America. Stanford University Press, Stanford, 624 pp." type="book" year="1958">
Keen, 
<number box="[1284,1351,918,944]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" value="1958.0">1958</number>
</bibRefCitation>
. Thus, 
<taxonomicName box="[151,366,956,982]" class="Bivalvia" family="Mytilidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mytiloida" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Mollusca" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Bathymodiolinae">Bathymodiolinae</taxonomicName>
would appear to be a grade of 
<taxonomicName box="[763,907,956,982]" class="Bivalvia" family="Mytilidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mytiloida" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Mollusca" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Modiolinae">Modiolinae</taxonomicName>
comprising several clades, each probably independently derived from small wood-associated ancestors (
<bibRefCitation author="Distel" box="[888,1031,993,1019]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" refString="Distel, D., Baco, A. R., Chuang, E., Morrill, W., Cavanaugh, C. &amp; Smith, C. R. (2000) Do mussels take wooden steps to deep-sea vents? Nature, 403, 725 - 726." type="journal article" year="2000">
Distel 
<number box="[968,1031,993,1019]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" value="2000.0">2000</number>
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Fujita" box="[1043,1251,993,1019]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" refString="Fujita, Y., Matsumoto, H., Fujiwara, Y., Hashimoto, J., Galkin, S. V., Ueshima, R. &amp; Miyazaki, J. - I. (2009) Phylogenetic relationships of deep-sea Bathymodiolus mussels to their mytilid relatives from sunken whale carcasses and wood. Venus, 67, 123 - 134." type="journal article" year="2009">
Fujita 
<emphasis box="[1119,1179,993,1018]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">et al.</emphasis>
<number box="[1187,1251,993,1019]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" value="2009.0">2009</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). Re-evaluation of the higher classification of mytilids is not our intention, and we consider it appropriate and convenient to refer to these mussels as bathymodiolines.
</paragraph>
